{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/constrained-linear-regression-aaf488296d93", "time": 1683011669.1058838, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/constrained-linear-regression-aaf488296d93/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Constrained Linear Regression. Market Mix Modelling | by Harsha Vardhan | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Constrained Linear Regression", "description": "When I first heard about \u201cConstrained Regression\u201d, I was perplexed as to why would someone want to constrain the coefficients which give you the optimal estimates for your data? Well, it turns out to\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://gain-insights.com/solutions/consumer-packaged-goods/marketing-mix-model/", "anchor_text": "Marketing Mix Model tool", "paragraph_index": 15}, {"url": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/harsha-vardhan-3094/", "anchor_text": "LinkedIn", "paragraph_index": 16}], "all_paragraphs": ["When I first heard about \u201cConstrained Regression\u201d, I was perplexed as to why would someone want to constrain the coefficients which give you the optimal estimates for your data? Well, it turns out to be one of the quintessential aspects of Market Mix Modeling and Price Promotion Optimization especially in Retail and CPG industries. I have divided the article into two sections which will be easy to follow.", "1. Why do we need Constrained Regression?", "2. Methods for performing Constrained Regression", "For a practical application, we turn to a concept called Market Mix Modeling (MMM). It helps in quantifying the impact of various marketing factors on sales or volume share. These marketing factors are mainly the 4Ps of marketing i.e., Price, Promotion, Product, and Place.", "If I increase the price of a product, what will happen to my sales? If I run a specific promotion, how my sales will change? It turns out, \u201cPrice\u201d and \u201cPromotion\u201d (continuous) are easily quantifiable whilst \u201cProduct\u201d and \u201cPlace\u201d (categorical) might need Mixed models.", "Performing a Multiple Linear Regression with Sales as the dependent variable and the marketing factors as independent variables can easily help to find the coefficients which quantify the impact of the respective factors.", "Note: In industry, professionals like to interchangeably use Market Mix Modeling, Media Mix Modeling, Price Elasticity Modeling etc., Having worked in all three modules, I would like to think Market Mix Modeling a parent module and Media Mix Modeling and Price Elasticity Modeling are sub modules.", "Let\u2019s say we are modeling some retail data with Sales as the dependent variable and Price of one of the products as one of the independent variables among a few others . The equation would be as below,", "The cost function of OLS can easily be transformed into the above equation and QP can thus be applied to solve with linear equality and inequality constraints.", "If we are constraining some coefficients, that means we have some prior knowledge on the estimates, which is what Bayesian Statistics deals with. We can specify a prior distribution on the estimates and perform the Bayesian regression to get the desired results.", "The above mentioned are not an exhaustive list and please feel free to add any other methods in the comment section.", "Let\u2019s consider some hypothetical data with Sales and Promotional spend as below.", "We shall perform Ordinary least squares and see what the results are.", "Let us constrain the coefficient of \u201cSpend\u201d to an arbitrary upper bound, say 0.5?", "Comparing the results in a tabular format as below,", "Well constraining the coefficient has cost us too much in terms of r2. And the package used above for constrained regression is a custom library made for Marketing Mix Model tool.", "Reach out to me on LinkedIn for any clarifications/feedback or if you want to collaborate on data science projects", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and co